The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Configure a Basic Security Context

Open New Terminal (Optional)

If current working directory is not workspace/.

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as workspace/ and change the directory as mentioned below.
mkdir -p course/7_protection_strategies/7.6_hardening
cd course/7_protection_strategies/7.6_hardening
ls

Immutable File System

  • Create a Kubernetes namespace for the application.
kubectl create namespace securitycontext

  • Save the pod.yaml & deploy the application to the Kubernetes cluster.
cat > pod.yaml <<EOF
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: security
  namespace: securitycontext
spec:
  containers:
  - image: busybox
    name: busybox
    args:
    - sleep
    - "1500"
EOF

  • Deploy the application to the Kubernetes cluster with readOnlyRootFilesystem set to false.
kubectl create -f pod.yaml

  • Execute the touch /tmp/file.txt command to create a file in the /tmp directory, 
kubectl exec -n securitycontext security -it -- touch /tmp/file.txt
  • Then execute the ls /tmp command to list the files in the /tmp directory.
kubectl exec -n securitycontext security -it -- ls /tmp

  • Delete the pod with readOnlyRootFilesystem set to false.
kubectl delete -f pod.yaml

  • Save the pod_true.yaml & deploy the application to the Kubernetes cluster with readOnlyRootFilesystem set to true.
cat > pod_true.yaml <<EOF
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: security-readonly
  namespace: securitycontext
spec:
  securityContext:
    runAsNonRoot: true
    runAsUser: 1000
    runAsGroup: 1000
  containers:
  - image: busybox
    name: busybox
    args:
    - sleep
    - "1500"
    securityContext:
      runAsUser: 2000
      readOnlyRootFilesystem: true
EOF

  • Deploy the application to the Kubernetes cluster with readOnlyRootFilesystem set to true.
kubectl create -f pod_true.yaml

  • Execute the touch /tmp/file.txt command to create a file in the /tmp directory.
kubectl exec -n securitycontext security-readonly -it -- touch /tmp/securitycontext.txt

  • Delete the pod.
kubectl delete -f pod_true.yaml
